		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2013"></a><br><code>sle2013/paper05</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> paper:</span><br><i>Software Evolution to Domain-Specific Languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/StefanFehrenbach.html">Stefan Fehrenbach</a>, <a href="../profile/SebastianErdweg.html">Sebastian Erdweg</a>, <a href="../profile/KlausOstermann.html">Klaus Ostermann</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_6">10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_6</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> The contribution proposes a process for evolving existing systems toward (embedded) DSL usage rather than rewriting from scratch.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The target outcome is adoption of embedded domain-specific languages to improve maintainability and tool support.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> The proposed evolution process relies on systematic program changes/refactorings that can be viewed as transformation steps toward DSL usage.
</li></ul></li></ul>
